04696nmm a2200697Ia 9781501728150DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017281507 a10.7591/97815017281502doi  a(DE-B1597)503553  a(OCoLC)1035322262  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY04a820.9/112qOCoLC223/eng/202302161 aSheehan, Elizabeth M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aModernism à la Mode :bFashion and the Ends of Literature /cElizabeth M. Sheehan. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (276 p.) :b10 b&w halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aModernism à la Mode argues that fashion describes why and how literary modernism matters in its own historical moment and ours. Bringing together texts, textiles, and theories of dress, Elizabeth Sheehan shows that writers, including Virginia Woolf, D.H. Lawrence, W.E.B. Du Bois, Nella Larsen, and F. Scott Fitzgerald, turned to fashion to understand what their own stylized works could do in the context of global capital, systemic violence, and social transformation. Modernists engage with fashion as a mood, a set of material objects, and a target of critique, and, in doing so, anticipate and address contemporary debates centered on the uses of literature and literary criticism amidst the supposed crisis in the humanities. A modernist affect with a purpose, no less.By engaging modernism à la mode—that is, contingently, contextually, and in light of contemporary concerns—this book offers an alternative to the often-untenable distinctions between strong or weak, suspicious or reparative, and politically activist or quietist approaches to literature, which frame current debates about literary methodology. As fashion helps us to describe what modernist texts do, it enables us to do more with modernism as a form of inquiry, perception, and critique. Fashion and modernism are interwoven forms of inquiry, perception, and critique, writes Sheehan. It is fashion that puts the work of early twentieth-century writers in conversation with twenty-first century theories of emotion, materiality, animality, beauty, and history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAmerican fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFashion in literature. 0aModernism (Literature)zGreat Britain. 0aModernism (Literature)zUnited States. 4aArt History. 4aFashion. 4aLiterary Studies.  aModernism, Fashion, Literature, Materiality, Affect.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060655308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2018 Englishz978311060418408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2018z9783110603187oZDB-23-DKU40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172815040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501728150423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501728150/original  a978-3-11-060418-4  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060425-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060655-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2017  aZDB-23